A text reminder will be sent to parents of in-school cohort students at approximately 6:30 AM on each assigned day.

The form can be accessed at https://tinyurl.com/y22s9dfb; please bookmark it or link it in a convenient location on a mobile device. FINLEY MIDDLE SCHOOL 2020-2021 STUDENT SCHEDULES NOW POSTED IN PARENT & STUDENT PORTALS ...

From Guidance Director Ms. Alomia:

I would like to inform you that your child's schedule for the 2020-2021 school year has been posted on the student and parent portals. If you would like to request a change in your child‚Äôs schedule please contact your child‚Äôs school counselor via email.

Paloma Herrera (pherrera@hufsd.edu)
Alison Logan (alogan@hufsd.edu)

They will respond to each request beginning the week of August 24th and continue through the first week of school.

This year, to ensure social distancing and safety practices are in place, students will be assigned to a cohort that corresponds to the day they attend school in person. As you know, the cohorts are in place as follows: Cohort 1: Alpha last name A-D (Tuesdays), Cohort 2: Alpha last name E-K (Wednesdays), Cohort 3: Alpha last name L-Ret (Thursdays) and Cohort 4: Alpha last name Rey-Z (Fridays). Students in Life Skills and 15:1:1 or 12:1 + (3:1) will attend school in person every day.

DIEGO TORRES TO STUDY CRIMINAL JUSTICE AT JOHN JAY COLLEGE ...

Diego Torres most certainly used his time wisely at Huntington High School, where he graduated with the Class of 2020 after achieving notable success in many areas. The teenager plans to study forensic science at CUNY John Jay College of Criminal Justice.

An Advanced Placement Scholar with Honor, Mr. Torres cites his ‚Äúability to understand concepts easily and minimize stress before exams‚Äù as the keys to his academic success. Surrounded by an exceptional group of friends, the teenagers have all encouraged and supported each other while embarking upon rigorous coursework.

Named a Distinguished Senior in recognition of his outstanding academic performance, Mr. Torres said the friendships he has developed made his journey through the high school an especially enjoyable one. Performing with the Blue Devil marching band, participating in the Environmental Club and competing with Huntington‚Äôs fencing team have all contributed to many happy days.

CHAOHAN YANG TO STUDY ACCOUNTING AT SUFFOLK CC ...

One of the top members of Huntington High School‚Äôs Class of 2020, Chaohan Yang excelled in a long list of Advanced Placement classes. The teenager plans to study accounting at Suffolk Community College in Brentwood.

An Advanced Placement Scholar with Distinction, Mr. Yang was a member of Huntington High School‚Äôs National Honor Society, Math Honor Society, English Honor Society, Science Honor Society and Social Studies Honor Society chapters.

Mr. Yang said he believes the opportunity to choose courses that he enjoyed and interested him has been the key to his academic success. He was able to further explore his interests through various high school activities which opened the door to meeting new people, forming friendships and having fun, he said.

JACK MONAHAN TO STUDY BUSINESS AT BINGHAMTON UNIVERSITY ...

Jack Monahan has taken a wide array of courses across every academic discipline and the Huntington High School Class of 2020 member has discovered where he career interests lie. He plans to study business at Binghamton University.

Mr. Monahan cites his natural intelligence along with guidance from his parents in helping him remain committed to obtaining good grades. His academic record was so strong that he qualified for the designation of Distinguished Senior.

A member of Huntington‚Äôs National Honor Society chapter, Mr. Monahan is an Advanced Placement Scholr with Honor. He played on the Blue Devil varsity golf, basketball and tennis teams, performed in the school band and participated in the high schools‚Äô environmental and yearbook clubs. A highlight was winning the school‚Äôs badminton tournament in 2019.

Mr. Monahan has found the social interaction he enjoyed with his friends to be an important part of his overall experience at Huntington High School.

ZADIE LAUER TO STUDY AT SUFFOLK CC ...

Zadie Lauer has found the key to her success is balance. The Huntington High School Class of 2020 member is interested in pursuing a degree in either environmental studies or political science. She plans to begin her studies at Suffolk Community College.

Ms. Lauer believes that it‚Äôs easy to become overwhelmed with schoolwork, but by putting aside time for the things she enjoys, including her friends and hobbies, she was able to be more productive when it was time for work.

The teenager has enjoyed watching herself grow as a person as well the entire high school learning experience. Ms. Lauer was able to form new friendships and discover her passions. She‚Äôs a strong advocate for racial justice, women‚Äôs rights and environmental justice and has worked with several organizations to advance her goals.

ANGELINA LARKIN TO STUDY ENGLISH AT ITHACA COLLEGE ...

Angelina Larkin is fascinated by the written and spoken word. The Huntington High School Class of 2020 member plans to study English at Ithaca College, where she also intends to carry a minor in art.

The teenager‚Äôs key to success is her drive to be the best she can possibly be at everything. An admitted perfectionist, Ms. Larkin garnered the designation of Distinguished Senior after four years of academic excellence. Inducted into several honor societies, she cast aside occasional hardships and challenges and grew in mind, body and spirit, discovering many friends she expects to maintain relationships with throughout life.

Ms. Larkin discovered her interests, as well as who she is and who she wants to be. Her strive for perfection has been a motivating force.

NAYELY ESTRADA-RODRIQUEZ CHOOSES LEMOYNE COLLEGE ...

Nayely Estrada-Rodriquez loves school so much she wants to make a career of it as a special education teacher. The Huntington High School Class of 2020 plans to study at LeMoyne University in Syracuse.

A member of the National Honor Society and the Spanish Honor Society, Ms. Estrada-Rodriquez captured the designation of Distinguished Senior after earning an academic grade average of 90 or better during every semester of high school.

Ms. Estrada-Rodriquez attributes her success to support from her parents and challenging herself in the classroom. The teenager found it important to pursue opportunities that moved her out of her comfort zone.

While compiling a strong academic record, Ms. Estrada-Rodriquez also participated in a full slate of extracurricular activities, including the China Club, United Amigos, A World of Difference and Natural Helpers.

Ms. Estrada-Rodriquez expressed appreciation for her ‚Äúamazing teachers who were always there to lend a hand‚Äù and who got her where she is today.

On Monday and Friday, Booster Club members will be collecting non-perishable items to support local community food backs. The group took the funds and bought an assortment of food items, which will be donated to local food pantries.

Community members are encouraged to donate whatever food items they can spare on Monday and Friday. The hungry need everyone‚Äôs help.

FINLEY'S JORDAN MATIJAK INKS CHILDREN'S BOOK ...

Congratulations to Jordan on writing her first book, "The Crazy Adventures of Izzy & Alex." The book was a labor of love for her, as Jordan's goal was to provide something to help cheer up young children (ages 4-8) during the pandemic.

Amazon provides an overview of the book, as follows ...

"Izzy and her older brother Alex are happy to move into their new home. They have more room to play and even get their very own rooms! Way to go, Jordan!! Keep on writing!

Her NFL career included an internship with the Buffalo Bills and positions with the NFL office and Atlanta Falcons before signing on with the Giants.

GRADUATION WEEKEND KICKS OFF, H-TON DRIVE-IN THEATER STYLE ...

It may not have been what was planned pre-pandemic, but it was a special night for the Class of 2020. Vehicles filled the grass field in front of Huntington High School to catch the premiere of Commencement 2020 and they were not disappointed.

The presentation opened with an array of nostalgic photos and continued with more traditional presentations and speeches, virtual style. The event was co-emceed by the talented duo of Keenan Lyons and Abby Semelsberger. It concluded with the presentation of approximately 400 graduates, certification of the class, and the "turning of the tassels."

Most importantly, we hope the night reflected how much love and pride we have for a simply outstanding group that is destined for greatness. They are not defined, but distinguished by the times and will come out on the other side of the pandemic even stronger. They will remain in our hearts and on our minds always!!

View the entire ceremony at http://huntington.mygrad.live. Use passcode: HHS6261900 for access.

EXCITING FINISH TO FIRST YEAR OF HOUSE PROGRAM AT JACK ABRAMS STEM ...

No pandemic could stop the kids and staff at Jack Abrams STEM from concluding the first full year of the school's House program (modeled after Hogwarts House in Pottermore) with an exclamation point.

Students were assigned to houses randomly at the beginning of the school year during an invigorating ceremony. Teams met periodically throughout the year to plan, develop their brand and associated cheers, and engage in service-related activities.

Each house is built on an important virtue ...

Altruismo - House of the Givers
Amistad - House of Friendship
Isibindi - House of Courage
Reveur - House of the Dreamers

It truly came down to the wire, but this year's winner is ... you'll need to watch to the end to find out. (In actuality, all students and staff are winners for participating in the program with tremendous energy and excitement!)

Special thanks to fifth grade teacher Emily Lohse for writing the song and editing the video, and to music teacher Katie Adams for singing!

https://youtu.be/40DxARb82zI

YOUTUBE.COM
Welcome To Our House (Jack Abrams STEM)

EXCITING FINISH TO FIRST YEAR OF HOUSE PROGRAM AT JACK ABRAMS STEM ...

No pandemic could stop the kids and staff at Jack Abrams STEM from concluding the first full year of the school's House program (modeled after Hogwarts House in Pottermore) with an exclamation point.

Students were assigned to houses randomly at the beginning of the school year during an invigorating ceremony. Teams met periodically throughout the year to plan, develop their brand and associated cheers, and engage in service-related activities.

Each house is built on an important virtue ...

Altruismo - House of the Givers
Amistad - House of Friendship
Isibindi - House of Courage
Reveur - House of the Dreamers

It truly came down to the wire, but this year's winner is ... you'll need to watch to the end to find out. (In actuality, all students and staff are winners for participating in the program with tremendous energy and excitement!)

Special thanks to fifth grade teacher Emily Lohse for writing the song and editing the video, and to music teacher Katie Adams for singing!

https://youtu.be/40DxARb82zI

YOUTUBE.COM
Welcome To Our House (Jack Abrams STEM)

SOON-TO-BE GRADUATES ARE HUNTINGTON PROUD & STRONG ...

As the final days of class are upon us, it is time to celebrate a group whose legacy will remain for the ages. The rock looks pretty darn beautiful following a marathon painting session from senior members of the Art Honor Society. Among quotes, hashtags and logos, it features the initials of every member of the Class of 2020.

Tremendous thanks to an amazing and incredibly creative group of young people - Daniela Ramos, Erik Flores, Niurca Chabla-Leon, Jazlyn Chapas-Oliva, Shyann Maragh, and Josie Fasolino! Additional thanks to Art Honor Society advisor Kim Valerio!

#HuntingtonProud
#HuntingtonStrong

JASON GIACHETTI IN RUNNING FOR PRESTIGIOUS NATIONAL MUSIC AWARD ...

HHS teacher Jason Giachetti is among a top group of American music teachers who woke up to exciting news this morning as the Recording Academy and GRAMMY Museum announced this year's quarterfinalists for the Music Educator Award. He is one of 216 music teachers from 199 cities recognized as a quarterfinalist for the prestigious honor.

The award was established to recognize current educators who have made a significant and lasting contribution to the field of music education and who demonstrate a commitment to the broader cause of maintaining music education in our nation's schools.

Congratulations, Mr. Giachetti!

Read more at https://www.grammy.com/press-releases/216-quarterfinalists-announced-2021-music-educator-award%E2%84%A2-presented-recording-academy

SENIOR MUSIC TALENTS GARNER NYSCAME SCHOLARSHIP AWARDS ...

Today, the New York State Council of Administrators in Music Education (NYSCAME) held its annual scholarship ceremony. Students from across Suffolk County and their families joined the membership of NYSCAME for the virtual event.

Each year, twelve Suffolk County graduating music students receive $1,000 scholarships toward their studies. This year, both Keenan Lyons and Abby Semelsberger earned awards!

Keenan earned the Robert Domencetti NYSCAME Scholarship. Mr. Domencetti served as director of the Huntington Community Band for many years and held the position of Director of Music Education for the Harborfields School District.

Abby was awarded the Robert W. Krueger NYSCAME Scholarship. Mr. Krueger worked as the Director of Music Education for the Northport-East Northport School District.

Congratulations to Keenan and Abby! This is only the beginning for these two incredible talents!

ROGER REES AWARDS PROGRAM ON MONDAY, JUNE 1 ...

Huntington High School's extraordinarily talented seniors Abby Semelsberger and Keenan Lyons were among an exclusive group of nominees for this year‚Äôs Roger Rees Awards for Excellence in Student Performance.

The 10th annual Roger Rees Awards program is being presented during an online special that will be streamed on the Broadway Education Alliance‚Äôs YouTube channel on Monday, June 1 at 7:30 p.m. Keenan is among the 25 male finalists!

The show will be hosted by Broadway ‚ÄúDear Evan Hansen‚Äù star and past Roger Rees Award and Jimmy Award recipient Andrew Barth Feldman and NY1‚Äôs Frank DiLella. The show will feature New York City-area theatre students performing musical numbers, including an opening performance of ‚ÄúAs Long as There is Love‚Äù from the new musical adaptation of ‚ÄúMrs. Doubtfire.‚Äù All 18 past Roger Reed Award winners (formerly known as the Gershwin Awards) will also perform.

FLAGS AT HALF STAFF FROM MAY 22-25 ...

Flags will lowered to half staff from May 22-24 to honor the memory of those lost to coronavirus and in support of their friends, families and colleagues.

Flags will remain at half staff from sunrise until noon on Memorial Day (Monday, May 25) to commemorate those who made the ultimate sacrifice as members of the military service.

post_text:
WAY TO GO, WASHINGTON THIRD GRADER DARREN KRANTZ, JR. ...

We can learn a great deal from our children! Great job, Darren!

News 12 reports ...

A 9-year-old go-kart driver has been extremely driven to help out during this pandemic in a big way.

Huntington's Darren Krantz Jr. started racing just two years ago with the logo for Angela's House all over his vehicle. It's a cause very dear to his family -- it works with hundreds of medically frail children every year.

"I just wanted to help the kids at Angela's House to make them feel better," says Krantz.

A little over a month ago, Krantz asked people to donate any amount they liked for every lap he raced. All of the money would go to buy food for Angela's House.

The result -- a tractor-trailer filled with food. Darren's dad says they raised over $50,000.

"I feel good about all the laps - because every lap I feel happy about it," Kratz says.

They plan to deliver the food to Angela's House Friday.
http://longisland.news12.com/story/42132324/driven-to-help-young-gokart-driver-raises-dollar50000-to-help-feed-medically-frail-kids

LONGISLAND.NEWS12.COM

HUNTINGTON HIGH SCHOOL 2020 SENIORS ARE A CLASS ACT ...

It was an emotional day for all, but an outstanding one nonetheless, as staff, parents and others paid visits to 425 high school seniors to express, in grand fashion, the greatest of love and support for an outstanding group.

Former NCAA basketball coach Jim Valvano once said, "If you laugh, you think and you cry, that's a full day. That's a heck of a day." It clearly describes today and we wouldn't change it for anything. Although it can't capture the full range of emotions, the video provides a taste of the experience.

And we can't say enough about how much our 2020 seniors mean to this school community, and how much we do and will always believe in them.

Stay strong, Class of 2020 seniors!! You got this!

Class of 2020 Huntington Blue Devil Strong

MAY 4-8 IS TEACHER APPRECIATION WEEK ... THANK YOU TO ALL HUNTINGTON STAFF MEMBERS!

Please take a moment to give thanks to our Huntington teachers who give so much to our children and each other under typical circumstances and who have truly stepped up during a challenging time.

And please give similar thanks to Huntington staff members in all capacities who are helping to keep things running in district as seamlessly as possibly. They include administrators and chairpersons, aides, teaching assistants and monitors, buildings and grounds crew members, clerical staff members, food service staff members, nurses, and security staff members. Many of these individuals are on the front line every day and continue to do outstanding work!

The common thread - they all care deeply about Huntington children and families.

Thank you to all!
